Spent today learning about the joys of self-employment
Namely, having to pay taxes quarterly.
yeah, you have to learn to ration out or at least mentally think all of the money isn't your money
regular jobs just snatch it away ahead of time so you don't think about it anyway
I *was* going to just take 20% of any money I got deposited into my account and move it to a savings account specifically for taxes
But what I didn't realize is that when you work for someone else, at least half of your Social Security / Medicare taxes are covered by your employer.
Generally called the "Self Employment Tax", 15.3% of your income will be taxed for that.
That said... the standard mileage deduction alone is reducing how much of my money is taxable by a rather huge margin
Yeah... hard lesson learned on my first day, haha.
First, as tempting as it is to start driving after finishing a delivery to move back towards restaurants, try sitting for a few minutes, you'll probably get an order if you're near them anyways.
And considering most restaurants are 5+ miles away from where I live, I don't want to do really short shifts.
First day, made $21, but thanks to the 29.62 miles I drove, I have a potential $16.58 tax reduction.
Obviously I'll need to work much longer shifts to see what kind of taxable income I have, but that doesn't seem that great.
Who knows, maybe I'll work a year and it turns out it's not that great of a gig for me
yeah, it's a change of pace at least
get to manage your own self, sorta
But I can't complain too much~
Hopefully I make some good money, haha
